🧠 What is PSI?
📌 PSI = Population Stability Index

👉 It is a statistical measure used to detect data drift.

🎯 Simple Meaning

PSI tells you whether your new data is different from your old (training) data

🧩 Why We Need PSI

In your project:

Model trained on old data
New users come with different behavior

👉 PSI checks:

“Is the data changing enough to break the model?”

🧠 Real-Life Example
Training Data (Old):
Income range: ₹20k – ₹50k
Loan amount: ₹1L – ₹5L
New Data (Current):
Income: ₹5k – ₹15k
Loan: ₹6L – ₹10L

👉 This is a big shift

➡️ PSI will detect:

🚨 Data distribution changed → model may fail

📊 PSI Values Interpretation
PSI Value	Meaning
< 0.10	✅ No Drift
0.10 – 0.25	⚠️ Moderate Drift
> 0.25	🚨 High Drift

👉 Your code already uses this correctly

🧮 How PSI Works (Conceptually)

PSI compares:

Expected distribution (old data)
Actual distribution (new data)
Formula (simplified idea):

For each bin:

PSI = Σ (Expected% - Actual%) * log(Expected% / Actual%)
🧠 Intuition

👉 If distributions are similar:

Expected ≈ Actual
PSI ≈ 0

👉 If distributions are different:

Big difference
PSI becomes large
📈 Example
Income Range	Old %	New %
0–20k	10%	40%
20–50k	70%	30%
50k+	20%	30%

👉 Big shift → PSI high → Drift detected 🚨

